  "prompt": "What are the best small classes for freshmen at Southern Connecticut State?",
  "response": "Southern Connecticut State University (SCSU) offers a variety of small classes across different disciplines that can provide a more personalized learning experience for freshmen. While specific course availability may vary by semester, here are some types of courses and recommendations that are generally well-received:\n\n1. **Introductory Courses in the Major**: Look for introductory classes in your intended major that typically have smaller enrollments. These can provide foundational knowledge and a sense of community among peers.\n\n2. **Freshman Seminars**: Many universities, including SCSU, offer freshman seminar courses designed to familiarize new students with college-level academics and university life. These classes often have a limited number of students.\n\n3. **General Education Courses**: Some general education courses, especially those in humanities or social sciences, tend to have smaller class sizes. Subjects like philosophy, sociology, or literature often provide engaging discussions.\n\n4. **Specialized Programs**: Some departments may offer specialized programs for freshmen that include small class settings, such as honors programs or living-learning communities.\n\n5. **Electives in Arts or Sciences**: Consider elective courses in creative writing, art, or environmental sciences, which can sometimes have smaller class sizes and offer an interactive learning environment.\n\nTo get the most accurate and up-to-date information, it\u2019s a good idea to check the university course catalog, talk to academic advisors, or reach out to faculty members. They can provide specific recommendations based on your interests and academic goals.",
